    <text xml:space="preserve">
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">
                <p> 
                    <lb n="1"/><unclear>//</unclear>ba <num value="3"><unclear>3</unclear></num> guna <num value="3">3</num> Apuy· <num value="3">3</num> 
                    <lb n="2"/> di <choice><reg>vvaṅ</reg><orig>vva</orig></choice> <num value="1">1</num>, Iti sakakala rumata<lb 
                        n="3" break="no"/> k· <choice><reg>disusuk ku</reg><orig>disusuku</orig></choice> baṭāri hyaṁ pun·</p>
            </div>
        <div type="apparatus">
            <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                   <lem><unclear>//</unclear>ba</lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Holle1877_01">// baḥ</rdg>
                     <rdg source="bib:HasanDjafar1991_01">// ba</rdg>
                     <note>We have doubt wether this is an opening or should be read as <foreign>A</foreign>. Noorduyn (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Noorduyn1993_01"/><citedRange>313</citedRange></bibl>) notes that <foreign>ba</foreign> means 3 in the chronogram of Pararaton. Zoetmulder (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Zoetmulder1982_01"/><citedRange unit="entry">wā</citedRange></bibl>records the word <foreign>ba</foreign> as a synonim of <foreign>wā</foreign> II 1. "live coal, piece of burning material which is aglow", and 2. = <foreign>ava</foreign> "bright, clear, shining".</note>
                 </app>
                <app loc="3">
                    <lem><choice><reg>disusuk ku</reg><orig>disusuku</orig></choice></lem>
                    <note>For the same phenomenon of consonant fusion, Cf. L 426B, nr. 13: hya <choice><reg>pəpək ku</reg><orig>pəpəku</orig></choice> pənuḥ kita maṁke "Now you are filled by fullness"</note>
                </app>
            </listApp>  
            </div>            
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
                <p>Shining 3 qualities 3 fires 3 in human 1: such is the <supplied reason="subaudible">year in the</supplied> Śaka era that Rumatak was marked off by Bhaṭārī Hyang. Finished. </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Despite that the scholars have determined the chronogram, only Saleh Danasasmita who furnish a full translation and interpretation. However, his reading seems less precise.</p>
            </div>
            
        <div type="bibliography">
           <p>The inscription was first published by Holle (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Holle1877_02"></ptr><citedRange>586-587</citedRange></bibl>, in Javanese script), follow by Saleh Danasasmita (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Saleh Danasasmita1975_01"></ptr></bibl>) and Hasan Djafar (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:HasanDjafar1991_01"></ptr><citedRange>16-18</citedRange></bibl>). Re-edited here by Aditia Gunawan &amp; Arlo Griffiths, using OD photo.</p>
